                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.943 Manchuria/44: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lockhart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-27T18:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 27, 1937—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 27—6:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>850. Embassy’s 843, December 24, noon. Following telegram has been sent to Mukden
                    and Harbin: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“December 27, 5 p.m. Your 16, December 23, 3 p.m. The Embassy considers
                            this matter to be covered by the Department’s 405, December 23, 7 p.m.,
                            transmitted to you by the Embassy’s December 26, 10 p.m., and you should
                            be governed by the principles therein established. The Embassy believes
                            the matter would best be dealt with orally on the occasion of your next
                            trip to Hsinking”<note n="82" xml:id="d1096fn82">The Department approved
                                this telegram in telegram No. 412, December 28, 7 p.m.</note>
                        </p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
